23 BE IT ENACTED BY THE PEOPLE OF THE STATE OF OKLAHOMA:
24
HB3698 HFLR Page 1
BOLD FACE denotes Committee Amendments.

1 SECTION 1. NEW LAW A new section of law to be codified
2 in the Oklahoma Statutes as Section 10-110 of Title 70, unless there
3 is created a duplication in numbering, reads as follows:
4 A. To help school districts address chronic absenteeism linked
5 to unstable housing, the "Student Eviction Assistance Pilot Program
6 Revolving Fund" is hereby created in the State Treasury for the
7 State Department of Education. The fund shall be a continuing fund,
8 not subject to fiscal year limitations, and shall consist of all
9 monies appropriated to or otherwise received by the State Department
10 of Education to provide legal services from funds appropriated to
11 the fund, federal funds, gifts, donations, and grants. All monies
12 accruing to the credit of said fund are hereby appropriated and may
13 be budgeted and expended by the State Department of Education for
14 the purpose of contracting for legal services to provide
15 representation for indigent tenants with children enrolled in a
16 public or private school in the State of Oklahoma pursuant to the
17 provisions of this section. Expenditures from said fund shall be
18 made upon warrants issued by the State Treasurer against claims
19 filed as prescribed by law with the Director of the Office of
20 Management and Enterprise Services for approval and payment.
21 B. To the extent funds are available, the State Department of
22 Education shall allocate funds from the Student Eviction Assistance
23 Pilot Program Revolving Fund to provide legal representation to
24
HB3698 HFLR Page 2
BOLD FACE denotes Committee Amendments.

1 indi gent persons with students enrolled in a public or private
2 school in pre-kindergarten through grade twelve:
3 1. In cities in this state that have a population of six
4 hundred thousand (600,000) or more, as determined by the last
5 Federal Decennial Census; and
6 2. In cities in this state that have a population of between
7 fifty thousand (50,000) and seventy-five thousand (75,000), as
8 determined by the last Federal Decennial Census, and are more than
9 sixty (60) miles from a city with a population of more than four
10 hundred thousand (400,000), as determined by the last Federal
11 Decennial Census,
12 for representation in forcible entry and detainer cases (commonly
13 referred to as eviction cases) filed pursuant to the Oklahoma
14 Residential Landlord and Tenant Act, Sections 1148.1 through 1148.16
15 of Title 12 of the Oklahoma Statutes. To qualify for
16 representation, the person must be referred to the legal services
17 organization by the school district where the student is enrolled.
18 C. The State Board of Education shall be responsible for
19 determining the service area for the legal services organization and
20 for allocating the funds pursuant to contracts with eligible
21 regional or statewide organizations which ordinarily render legal
22 services to indigent persons. The State Department of Education may
23 charge an administrative fee for administering the contracts. The
24 funds shall be allocated for the benefit of indigent persons with
HB3698 HFLR Page 3
BOLD FACE denotes Committee Amendments.

1 stud ents enrolled in a public or private school in pre-kindergarten
2 through grade twelve in all seventy-seven (77) counties of the state
3 on a formula to be determined by the State Board of Education,
4 utilizing an allocation formula that distributes funds according to
5 the number of residents whose incomes are less than the official
6 United States federal poverty guidelines, based on United States
7 census data, as a percentage of the total number of these residents
8 in this state and on the percentage of students within the school
9 district reported to be chronically absent in the previous school
10 year.
11 D. As used in this section, "eligible organization" means an
12 entity that:
13 1. Is organized as a not-for-profit corporation that is tax
14 exempt pursuant to the provisions of Section 501(c)(3) of the United
15 States Internal Revenue Code of 1986, as amended; and
16 2. Is incorporated pursuant to any applicable laws of this
17 state.
18 E. As a condition of the contract, the organization shall be
19 required to determine the eligibility of any person seeking legal
20 services pursuant to this section.
21 F. The State Department of Education shall prepare annually and
22 distribute to the Governor, the President Pro Tempore of the
23 Oklahoma State Senate and the Speaker of the Oklahoma House of
24 Representatives a report detailing expenditures of funds.
HB3698 HFLR Page 4
BOLD FACE denotes Committee Amendments.

1 G. Each organization that contracts to provide legal services
2 pursuant to subsection B of this section shall maintain books and
3 records in accordance with generally accepted accounting principles.
4 The books and records shall account for the receipt and expenditure
5 of all funds paid pursuant to contract. Books and records shall be
6 maintained for a period of five (5) years from the close of the
7 fiscal year of the contract period. The State Auditor and Inspector
8 may audit each organization annually. The necessary expense of each
9 audit, including, but not limited to, the cost of typing, printing,
10 and binding, shall be paid from funds of the organization. In lieu
11 of the audit by the State Auditor and Inspector, the organization
12 may submit an audit prepared by an independent auditing firm for
13 compliance with federal auditing requirements. A copy of the audit
14 prepared by or submitted to the State Auditor and Inspector shall be
15 submitted to the Attorney General.
16 H. This pilot program shall terminate three (3) years after the
17 effective date of this act.
18 SECTION 2. This act shall become effective November 1, 2026.
